        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Cheung",
        "timestamp": 1741111686
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do you know what <code>% 0</code> means?</p>",
        "id": 503332460,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1741111739
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Basically, <code>a %  0 = a</code>. But using <code>rw [Nat.mod_zero]</code> didn't do anything.</p>",
        "id": 503332548,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Cheung",
        "timestamp": 1741111771
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's because it's <code>Fin</code> mod, not <code>Nat</code> mod.<br>\n<a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Fin.instMod#doc\">docs#Fin.instMod</a></p>",
        "id": 503332612,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1741111797
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see. But there seems to be no <code>Fin.mod_zero</code>.</p>",
        "id": 503332773,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Cheung",
        "timestamp": 1741111846
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can use <code>Fin.mod_def</code> and <code>Nat.mod_zero</code> instead until someone adds a <code>Fin.mod_zero</code>.</p>",
        "id": 503333137,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1741111968
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>After <code>Fin.mod_def</code>, I now have <code>h : ⟨↑(a - ↑↑k) % ↑0, ⋯⟩ = ⟨↑(b - ↑↑k) % ↑0, ⋯⟩</code> in the context. How do I use <code>Nat.mod_zero</code> to simplify the stuff inside the angle brackets? <code>rw</code> couldn't seem to get inside.</p>",
        "id": 503334131,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Cheung",
        "timestamp": 1741112306
    },
